<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-01-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-01-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="1295" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1295">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/10533.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Edwards</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Acapulco</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-12">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 12, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Mariscal has entered Acapulco with 300 men asking for money and
                            ammunition. The military commander made forced loans yesterday in order
                            to raise money to pay the former’s troops including the Americans in his
                            demands and threatening that Mariscal would not wait. There is great
                            apprehension of trouble and the garrison is entirely insufficient to
                            afford protection. Embassy advised.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Edwards</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>